ties to explore and learn about reconciliation praxis and responsibilities. By implementing arts based counter-narratives set against Settler Canadian history and geography, Smallest Circles First considers the implications of systemic racism, colonization, and political, social, and economic ramifications of governmental policies. Tangible examples from the book showcase how teachers and students can use the arts to learn specifically about their responsibilities in engaging with the TRC, in addition to how this work can still meet curricular learning outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDrama in educationzQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 0aTeacher participation in curriculum planningzQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 0aTeaching, Freedom ofzQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 7aEDUCATION / Multicultural Education.2bisacsh  aIndigenous studies.  aTRC.  aarts based methods.  aautophenomenology.  acurriculum studies.  adrama and theatre education.  ainservice.  areconciliation.  ateacher professional development.1 aCarter, Mindy R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDearhouse, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayden-Benn, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolodziechuk, Alayna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753221540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487532215423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487532215/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles